  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Land, Territory and Food Security for Four Indigenous Peoples of Bahia and Ceara</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The indigenous peoples of Northeast Brazil have faced constant violations of their territorial and cultural rights, as well as their right to adequate nutrition. The rights to which these groups are entitled by law are not enforced, but indigenous peoples also face pressure from mega projects, such as the Project to Transfer the Waters of the S&#xE3;o Francisco River and dam-building. Despite these challenges, these people have a history of valiant resistance and continue to seek ways to regain and defend their territories, their traditions and their livelihoods. This project will strengthen the connection between regaining territories and constructing sustainable production systems, on the basis of agroecology. This innovative proposal will involve 120 original indigenous families and more than 180 through Passing on the Gift, among the Tumbalal&#xE1; and Tupinamb&#xE1; peoples, in Bahia and the Tabajara/Kalaba&#xE7;a and Kanind&#xE9; peoples, in Cear&#xE1;. It will contribute to strengthening a chain of solidarity in the quest for food sovereignty and security.</narrative>
  </description>
